203.text: Daniel Geschwind , a neurogeneticist at the University of California , Los Angeles

quotes.text: "Both twins came into the world with the same set of high risks for developing MS,"
quotes.speaker: Kingsmore

quotes.text: "There had to be some trigger that caused one to develop it and the other not,"
quotes.speaker: Kingsmore

quotes.text: "one was exposed to the perfect combination of environmental triggers"
quotes.speaker: Baranzini

quotes.text: "What they've done here is create a very nice template for others to follow,"
quotes.speaker: Geschwind

quotes.text: "It isn't just sequence — they went from sequence to epigenome to expression. That's what really makes [the study] something special."
quotes.speaker: Baranzini

quotes.text: "If we sequenced another dozen twin pairs we could make this much more definitive,"
quotes.speaker: Kingsmore

quotes.text: "we really ought to look at sequencing of the brain tissue,"
quotes.speaker: Baranzini
